WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.520
 So now we're going to talk about JavaScript functions

00:00:02.520 --> 00:00:05.040
 and JavaScript arrays.

00:00:05.040 --> 00:00:08.920
 So functions use the function keyword.

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:10.920
 Unlike Python, this would be like in the DEF,

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:13.920
 this would be like DEF in Python.

00:00:13.920 --> 00:00:19.560
 And so we basically say function and then

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:21.760
 give the name of a function and then the parameters

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:23.000
 to the function.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.720
 And then you have a curly brace to start the function

00:00:25.720 --> 00:00:26.720
 and then end the function.

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:31.240
 This is over here.

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:34.360
 And then you have return to return the resulting value.

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:38.000
 And that return defines the return value

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:39.840
 that's going to be used in some expression.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:42.880
 So you're cruising along, you're in the middle of an expression,

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:45.960
 you encounter a function, it calls the function, runs the call,

00:00:45.960 --> 00:00:47.880
 and then the return value is what

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:50.920
 is the residual that's placed in that plus.

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:53.640
 So whatever that value is, in this case,

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:59.200
 it's going to add 4 and 5 and end up with 9

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:01.120
 as the result, and prod equals 9.

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:08.560
 So the functions, other than that,

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:14.600
 are like most programming languages,

00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:16.600
 except when it comes to global variables.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:20.760
 And so most of the time when you're working with a function,

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:26.000
 every variable that you define inside the function

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:27.520
 is local to that function.

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:29.960
 And so if you use the same variable outside the function,

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:31.440
 now I'm doing this two lines away,

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:34.480
 but really often this function's inside of a library

00:01:34.480 --> 00:01:36.200
 and it doesn't even know what variables are

00:01:36.200 --> 00:01:38.120
 being used outside of it.

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:42.000
 And so by default, these two are the same.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.520
 And I'm not really familiar of a lot of other programming

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:48.600
 languages where the default is that that's

00:01:48.600 --> 00:01:51.360
 kind of a global variable if you don't make it worse.

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:53.440
 It depends on whether this global variable is defined

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:55.440
 before or after turn 2.

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:58.040
 In this case, I'm defining the global variable before,

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:02.960
 and I say nothing special about gl, and so it's global.

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:07.160
 And so I set it to 123, then I call this function,

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:08.800
 and it sets it to 456.

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:13.160
 And when we come back from the function, it's 456.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:14.520
 So that's kind of weird.

00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:17.640
 It's this weird kind of super global

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:20.600
 by default, which is not the way we usually

00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:22.840
 like to run functions.

00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:25.520
 So what we do, and it's really weird.

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:29.720
 There's no other programming language that makes you say,

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:30.600
 don't be global.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:31.920
 Most other programming languages,

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:34.640
 if they have a global capability and not all of them do,

00:02:34.640 --> 00:02:37.240
 they're like, this is the weird one that's global

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:39.060
 and everything else is local.

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:41.200
 What you do is if you don't say it's local,

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:42.880
 it's going to be global.

00:02:42.880 --> 00:02:47.800
 So the var keyword basically says, it's local.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:52.120
 It's just, this is a variable and it's local.

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:57.120
 And so I can say, var gl equals 456.

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:01.640
 That means that that variable has no effect

00:03:01.640 --> 00:03:04.000
 outside the function, i.e. the function lives

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.240
 in its own little silo, which is the way

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:09.440
 most functions usually work unless we explicitly

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:11.400
 bust out of the little silo.

00:03:11.400 --> 00:03:14.440
 So in this case, if we do gl equals 123,

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:16.920
 then we call function check, and we look at gl,

00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:19.960
 even though inside a function there's a gl that's 456,

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:24.120
 not the same gl, and so we get 123

00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:25.720
 when it's all said and done.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:27.640
 So that's really quite nice.

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:30.040
 But you do put a lot of vars in,

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:34.040
 and one of my biggest bugs when I write JavaScript

00:03:34.040 --> 00:03:35.380
 is to forget to put the var in.

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:38.040
 So I now just kind of been punished enough to know,

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:41.960
 always put the var in so you get what you kind of expect

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:44.560
 as a default in most other programming languages

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:48.720
 that all variables that are defined inside of a function

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:51.920
 are local unless you're very explicitly doing otherwise.

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:55.000
 JavaScript has arrays.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.500
 They look a lot like Python lists.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:02.660
 So here we have an array that's three strings.

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:06.660
 JavaScript has an associative structure,

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:08.440
 but it's not an associative array,

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:12.400
 and it's more like a dictionary, but it's not.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:14.080
 It's an object.

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:16.640
 Objects can be many, many things,

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:18.440
 and we'll talk a bunch, we'll have a whole lecture

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:19.760
 on nothing but objects.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:22.080
 But right now they kind of look like a dictionary.

00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:24.360
 Key, value, pair, key, value, pair.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:26.480
 Key is name, value is chuck.

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:28.760
 Key is class, value is DJ4E.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:31.780
 And so when you print that out, away you go.

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:35.280
 Now, you can say a sub zero, which gives you x,

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:36.520
 which is that first element,

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:39.840
 and you can say b sub quote, name, quote.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:41.320
 You can do that.

00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:43.900
 Another way to say that is b dot name.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:48.960
 Those two syntaxes, and this confused the heck out of me

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:51.240
 when I was first learning JavaScript,

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:53.800
 those two syntaxes mean the same thing.

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:58.720
 They both are saying look up an attribute

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:01.740
 of the object b that's named name.

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:06.560
 And again, equivalently, they are the same thing,

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:09.600
 even though for every other language you ever look at,

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:12.520
 you think those are very different creatures,

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:14.000
 but not so in JavaScript.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.800
 And it has to do with the fact that b is an object.

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:17.760
 It is an object.

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:20.440
 And so objects are the associative structures,

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:23.840
 but they're even more powerful than associative arrays

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:28.780
 are in some languages, like directories.

00:05:28.780 --> 00:05:32.880
 Linear arrays, you can make linear arrays.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:35.400
 You can fill them up a couple different ways.

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:37.520
 You can either fill them up, you know,

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:38.760
 we start and make an array,

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:41.080
 and we can push some elements in.

00:05:41.080 --> 00:05:43.520
 I don't like the name push, I like append better.

00:05:43.520 --> 00:05:46.140
 That would be what we would say if we were in Python,

00:05:46.140 --> 00:05:48.720
 if this were a list, but it works.

00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:50.720
 Push kind of pushes onto the end.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:52.840
 Normally push means push onto the beginning,

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:56.880
 but in computer science, push usually means push down,

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:00.600
 not append, but so I think Python has a JavaScript there

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:05.080
 where we say append in Python, we say push in JavaScript,

00:06:05.080 --> 00:06:08.160
 or we can just fill it up with the array,

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:10.560
 array sub zero and array sub one,

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:13.000
 and then we can fill up a nice linear array

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.880
 if we want, and remember, in JavaScript,

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:19.140
 arrays are arrays, they're not dictionaries,

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:20.400
 they are lists.

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:25.080
 In Python, Python has lists and dictionaries,

00:06:25.080 --> 00:06:28.100
 and JavaScript has arrays and objects.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:31.180
 There's other syntaxes for making arrays.

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:34.200
 You can say array and then just have a list of things

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:36.340
 that make up the array, and you get an array,

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:39.540
 or you just use the constant form, that square brackets,

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:42.920
 and this looks exactly like how we would do it in Python,

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:46.080
 and so that works, so in that particular line,

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:49.760
 you can write Python in JavaScript if you so desire.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:52.760
 Up next, we're gonna talk about control structures.

00:06:52.760 --> 00:06:55.340
 (upbeat music)

